 "C3": "2 full"}, "feature_key": "bath", "diff_comps": ["C2"], "diff_directions": {"C2": "superior"}}, {"label": "Bedrooms", "subject": "3", "comp_values": {"C1": "3", "C2": "3", "C3": "3"}, "diff_comps": []}, {"label": "Garage", "subject": "2-car", "comp_values": {"C1": "2-car", "C2": "2-car", "C3": "2-car"}, "diff_comps": []}, {"label": "Year Built", "subject": "1998", "comp_values": {"C1": "1999", "C2": "1998", "C3": "1997"}, "diff_comps": []}, {"label": "Condition", "subject": "Good", "comp_values": {"C1": "Good", "C2": "Good", "C3": "Good"}, "diff_comps": []}], "step2": {"tabs": [{"key": "paired", "label": "Paired Sales Analysis", "intro": "Use the supporting market data — all confirmed from the retrospective market period as of the date of death — to derive contributory values. Two paired sales tables, one per adjustment type. For IRS review, your methodology and data sources must be clearly documented.", "tables": [{"kind": "paired_dollar_per_unit", "feature_key": "gla", "title": "GLA Pairs — Calculate $/SF (Retrospective Data)", "instruction": "Each pair confirmed equivalent except GLA, all from the retrospective market period. Divide Price Difference ÷ SF Difference. Pairs cluster tightly — strong market support for the IRS review standard.", "input_label": "Your $/SF", "input_suffix": "/SF", "rows": [{"label": "1", "cells": ["1,730 SF / $262,000", "1,880 SF / $269,100", "150 SF", "$7,100"]}, {"label": "2", "cells": ["1,780 SF / $266,500", "1,930 SF / $273,800", "150 SF", "$7,300"]}, {"label": "3", "cells": ["1,820 SF / $270,000", "1,970 SF / $277,350", "150 SF", "$7,350"]}], "column_headers": ["Pair", "Sale A (SF / Price)", "Sale B (SF / Price)", "SF Diff", "Price Diff"], "concluded_label": "Concluded GLA Adjustment", "concluded_helper": "Bracket your three results — pairs cluster tightly."}, {"kind": "paired_dollar_diff", "feature_key": "bath", "title": "Bathroom Pairs — 2 Full vs. 2.5 Baths (Retrospective)", "instruction": "Pairs isolate the bathroom count difference. All pairs confirmed from the retrospective market period. Subtract the 2-full-bath sale price from the 2.5-bath sale price.", "input_label": "Your Price Difference", "input_suffix": "", "rows": [{"label": "1", "cells": ["$265,000", "$271,300"]}, {"label": "2", "cells": ["$270,500", "$277,100"]}], "column_headers": ["Pair", "2 Full Bath Sale", "2.5 Bath Sale"], "concluded_label": "Concluded Bathroom Adjustment", "concluded_helper": "Bracket your two results."}]}, {"key": "cost", "label": "Cost-Based Support", "intro": "Calculate the depreciated contributory value for both adjustment types, using cost data adjusted to the retrospective effective date. Note carefully: both cost indications fall BELOW the paired sales range — cost acts as a floor here, not a ceiling. The market pays above depreciated replacement cost for this property type and vintage. Market evidence (paired sales) governs in both cases; cost defines the lower boundary.", "items": [{"kind": "cost_calc", "feature_key": "gla", "title": "GLA Contributory Value ($/SF) — Retrospective", "fact_rows": [["RCN (retrospective)", "$75.00 / SF"], ["Effective Age", "26 years"], ["Economic Life", "60 years"], ["Depreciation Rate", "26 ÷ 60 = 43.3%"], ["Formula", "$75.00 × (1 − 0.433) = ?"]], "input_suffix": "/SF"}, {"kind": "cost_calc", "feature_key": "bath", "title": "Bathroom Cost (Half-Bath Addition) — Retrospective", "fact_rows": [["Cost (retrospective)", "$10,500"], ["Effective Age", "26 years"], ["Economic Life", "60 years"], ["Depreciation Rate", "43.3%"], ["Formula", "$10,500 × (1 − 0.433) = ?"]], "input_suffix": ""}]}], "reconciliation": {"instruction": "Review both method indications and enter your reconciled adjustment for each item. Both cost indications fall below the paired sales range — cost is a floor here. Weight the paired sales evidence in your reconciliation and explain the cost relationship in your rationale.", "items": [{"feature_key": "gla", "label": "GLA Adjustment ($/SF)"}, {"feature_key": "bath", "label": "Bathroom Adjustment ($)"}]}}, "step3": {"instruction": "Apply your reconciled adjustments to each comparable. Use a NEGATIVE value where the comp is superior to the subject, and a POSITIVE value where it is inferior. Comps 1 and 3 both require GLA adjustments but in opposite directions (Comp 1 larger, Comp 3 smaller). For IRS review, your rationale should explicitly confirm that all data reflects the retrospective effective date and address the cost-as-floor relationship.", "applicable": {"C1": ["gla"], "C2": ["bath"], "C3": ["gla"]}, "method_dropdown": ["Paired Sales Analysis", "Grouped Paired Sales", "Cost-Based Support", "Income Differential / GRM", "Regression Analysis", "Appraiser Judgment / Extraction"], "support_min_chars": 15}, "step4": {"show_net_gross_panel": false}}'::jsonb,
  '{"step1_correct_flags": {"C1": ["gla"], "C2": ["bath"], "C3": ["gla"]}, "step1_rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior GLA, requires negative adjustment). Comp 2 has 2.5 bathrooms versus the subject''s 2 full (superior, requires negative adjustment). Comp 3 is 120 SF smaller than the subject (inferior GLA, requires positive adjustment). Sale dates are within 3 months of the retrospective effective date — no market conditions adjustment required at this level. All other features are equivalent across all three comparables.", "step2_tables": {"paired": {"gla": {"pair_answers": [47.33, 48.67, 49.0], "concluded_range": [47.0, 49.0], "rationale": "Three pairs produce $47.33, $48.67, and $49.00/SF — a tight $1.67 spread that constitutes strong, consistent market support. All pairs confirmed from the retrospective market period. Reconcile near the midpoint."}, "bath": {"pair_answers": [6300, 6600], "concluded_range": [6250, 6650], "rationale": "Two pairs bracket the half-bath increment at $6,300 and $6,600 — tight retrospective market support."}}, "cost": {"gla": {"answer": 42.53, "rationale": "$75.00 × (1 − 0.433) = $42.53/SF (retrospective). Falls BELOW the paired sales range of $47–$49/SF — cost is a floor here. The market is paying above depreciated replacement cost for this 1998 vintage. Market evidence (paired sales) governs; cost defines the lower boundary."}, "bath": {"answer": 5954, "rationale": "$10,500 × (1 − 0.433) = $5,954 (retrospective). Falls below paired sales of $6,300–$6,600 — again a floor. Conclude toward paired sales range."}}}, "step2_reconciliation": {"gla": {"range": [47.0, 49.0], "rationale": "Three retrospective paired sales support $47–$49/SF tightly. Cost support of $42.53/SF falls below the paired range — a floor in this scenario rather than the typical ceiling. The market pays above depreciated replacement cost for this property type and vintage. Weight paired sales heavily; reconcile near $48/SF."}, "bath": {"range": [6300, 6600], "rationale": "Two paired sales bracket $6,300–$6,600. Cost support of $5,954 again falls below paired sales — a floor. Reconcile within the paired bracket."}}, "step3_adjustments": {"C1": {"gla": {"direction": "negative", "amount_per_unit": -48.0, "units": 150, "computed_amount": -7200, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior). At the reconciled rate of $48/SF (drawn from three tightly-clustered retrospective pairs), the GLA adjustment is −$7,200. Cost support of $42.53/SF acts as a floor; the market pays above replacement cost for this vintage."}}, "C2": {"bath": {"direction": "negative", "amount": -6450, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 2 has 2.5 bathrooms versus the subject''s 2 full (superior). The half-bath increment from two retrospective paired sales is approximately $6,450 (midpoint of $6,300–$6,600). Cost support of $5,954 again falls below paired sales — confirms the cost-as-floor pattern across both adjustment types in this scenario."}}, "C3": {"gla": {"direction": "positive", "amount_per_unit": 48.0, "units": 120, "computed_amount": 5760, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 3 is 120 SF smaller than the subject (inferior). At the reconciled rate of $48/SF, the GLA adjustment is +$5,760."}}}, "step4_adjusted_prices": {"C1": {"unadjusted": 291000, "adjusted": 283800}, "C2": {"unadjusted": 286500, "adjusted": 280050}, "C3": {"unadjusted": 271000, "adjusted": 276760}}, "step4_reconciliation_narrative": "Adjusted prices cluster in a tight band of approximately $276,760–$283,800 — a spread of roughly $7,000. The three adjusted comparables, all confirmed within 6 months of the date of death, produce this indicated range under the IRS Revenue Ruling 59-60 Fair Market Value standard. The basic-level teaching point is the cost-as-floor relationship: in prior modules, cost typically exceeded paired sales and acted as a ceiling, but here both GLA ($42.53/SF) and bathroom ($5,954) cost indications fall BELOW the paired sales range. The market is paying a premium above depreciated replacement cost for this 1998 vintage in an established neighborhood. In both cases — cost as ceiling and cost as floor — the market evidence governs and the cost indication defines the boundary. The retrospective effective date and all supporting data must be clearly documented in the written appraisal report for IRS Form 706 reporting.", "tolerance_note": "Student answers are accepted within ±5% of model derived values for paired-sales calculations and within the indicated reconciliation range. Step 3 adjustments accepted within ±13% of the computed amount for GLA and ±12% for bath."}'::jsonb
