cluded GLA Adjustment", "concluded_helper": "Bracket toward Pairs 1 & 2; address Pair 3 explicitly."}, {"kind": "paired_dollar_diff", "feature_key": "bath", "title": "Bathroom Pairs — 2.5 vs. 3 Full Baths (Retrospective)", "instruction": "Pairs isolate the bathroom count difference. All pairs confirmed from the retrospective market period. Subtract the 2.5-bath sale price from the 3-full-bath sale price.", "input_label": "Your Price Difference", "input_suffix": "", "rows": [{"label": "1", "cells": ["$306,000", "$313,000"]}, {"label": "2", "cells": ["$299,500", "$306,700"]}], "column_headers": ["Pair", "2.5 Bath Sale", "3 Full Bath Sale"], "concluded_label": "Concluded Bathroom Adjustment", "concluded_helper": "Bracket your two results."}, {"kind": "paired_pct_per_month", "feature_key": "date", "title": "Market Conditions — Retrospective Resale Pair Analysis", "instruction": "The same properties sold twice during the retrospective market period. For each pair, calculate the monthly appreciation rate using: (Resale − Original) ÷ Original ÷ Months × 100. All resale dates confirmed pre-date-of-death.", "input_label": "Your %/Month", "input_suffix": "%/mo", "rows": [{"label": "A", "cells": ["$290,000", "$299,480", "11"]}, {"label": "B", "cells": ["$302,000", "$311,262", "10"]}, {"label": "C", "cells": ["$296,000", "$306,000", "9"]}], "column_headers": ["Property", "Original Sale Price", "Resale Price", "Months"], "concluded_label": "Concluded Monthly Rate", "concluded_helper": "Bracket your three results."}]}, {"key": "cost", "label": "Cost-Based Support", "intro": "GLA and bathroom have cost support adjusted to the retrospective effective date. Market conditions has no applicable cost method. Note the shift from the basic-level scenario: GLA cost now falls near the top of the paired sales range — a mild ceiling rather than a floor.", "items": [{"kind": "cost_calc", "feature_key": "gla", "title": "GLA Contributory Value ($/SF) — Retrospective", "fact_rows": [["RCN (retrospective)", "$78.00 / SF"], ["Effective Age", "22 years"], ["Economic Life", "60 years"], ["Depreciation Rate", "22 ÷ 60 = 36.7%"], ["Formula", "$78.00 × (1 − 0.367) = ?"]], "input_suffix": "/SF"}, {"kind": "cost_calc", "feature_key": "bath", "title": "Bathroom Cost (Full Bath Addition) — Retrospective", "fact_rows": [["Cost (retrospective)", "$13,000"], ["Effective Age", "22 years"], ["Economic Life", "60 years"], ["Depreciation Rate", "36.7%"], ["Formula", "$13,000 × (1 − 0.367) = ?"]], "input_suffix": ""}]}], "reconciliation": {"instruction": "Review both method indications and enter your reconciled adjustment for each item. GLA cost is near the top of the paired sales range — a mild ceiling; both methods converge. Bathroom cost exceeds paired sales — weight paired sales. Market conditions reconciles directly from resale pairs.", "items": [{"feature_key": "gla", "label": "GLA Adjustment ($/SF)"}, {"feature_key": "bath", "label": "Bathroom Adjustment ($)"}, {"feature_key": "date", "label": "Market Conditions Adjustment (%/mo)"}]}}, "step3": {"instruction": "Apply your reconciled adjustments to each comparable. All adjustments reflect retrospective effective date conditions. Use a NEGATIVE value where the comp is superior to the subject, and a POSITIVE value where it is inferior. For Comp 3 (market conditions), calculate as: $289,000 × 9 months × your reconciled %/mo ÷ 100. Each rationale should explicitly confirm that supporting data reflects conditions as of the date of death.", "applicable": {"C1": ["gla"], "C2": ["bath"], "C3": ["date"]}, "method_dropdown": ["Paired Sales Analysis", "Market Conditions (Resale Pairs)", "Cost-Based Support", "Grouped Paired Sales", "Regression Analysis", "Appraiser Judgment / Extraction"], "support_min_chars": 15}, "step4": {"show_net_gross_panel": false}}'::jsonb,
  '{"step1_correct_flags": {"C1": ["gla"], "C2": ["bath"], "C3": ["date"]}, "step1_rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior GLA, single adjustment). Comp 2 has 3 full bathrooms versus the subject''s 2.5 (superior bath, single adjustment). Comp 3 sold 9 months prior to the retrospective effective date in an appreciating market (inferior date, single adjustment). All other features (bedrooms, garage, year built, condition) are equivalent across all three comparables. All adjustments reflect retrospective effective date conditions.", "step2_tables": {"paired": {"gla": {"pair_answers": [48.33, 48.67, 58.0], "concluded_range": [48.0, 50.0], "rationale": "Pairs 1 and 2 cluster tightly at $48.33 and $48.67/SF — consistent retrospective market evidence. Pair 3 diverges significantly to $58.00/SF and must be excluded with documented reasoning for IRS review (different submarket, anomalous transaction, or data anomaly). Bracket conclusion toward Pairs 1 & 2."}, "bath": {"pair_answers": [7000, 7200], "concluded_range": [6900, 7300], "rationale": "Two pairs bracket the half-bath increment at $7,000 and $7,200 — tight retrospective support."}, "date": {"pair_answers": [0.298, 0.307, 0.376], "concluded_range": [0.28, 0.39], "rationale": "Three retrospective resale pairs produce 0.30%, 0.31%, and 0.38%/mo. Pairs A and B cluster tightly; Pair C is somewhat higher. Bracket toward central tendency near 0.32%/mo, with confidence that the appreciation rate sits in the lower part of the wider range."}}, "cost": {"gla": {"answer": 49.37, "rationale": "$78.00 × (1 − 0.367) = $49.37/SF (retrospective). Falls near the top of the consistent paired sales range ($48.33–$48.67/SF) — a mild ceiling. Both methods are closely aligned, providing convergent support that strengthens defensibility for IRS review."}, "bath": {"answer": 8229, "rationale": "$13,000 × (1 − 0.367) = $8,229 (retrospective). Significantly exceeds paired sales of $7,000–$7,200 — cost is a clear ceiling. Weight paired sales in reconciliation."}}}, "step2_reconciliation": {"gla": {"range": [48.0, 50.0], "rationale": "Paired sales support $48.33–$48.67/SF (Pairs 1 & 2). Pair 3 ($58.00/SF) excluded with documented retrospective reasoning. Cost support of $49.37/SF falls just above the paired range — mild ceiling, methods converge. This convergence is particularly valuable under IRS review; reconcile near $49/SF."}, "bath": {"range": [7000, 7200], "rationale": "Paired sales bracket $7,000–$7,200 in retrospective data. Cost of $8,229 exceeds paired sales — clear ceiling. Reconcile within the paired bracket."}, "date": {"range": [0.31, 0.35], "rationale": "Paired sales support a wider range of 0.30–0.38%/mo. Two pairs cluster near 0.30%, one higher at 0.38%. No cost method applicable. Reconcile near the central tendency at approximately 0.33%/mo."}}, "step3_adjustments": {"C1": {"gla": {"direction": "negative", "amount_per_unit": -49.0, "units": 150, "computed_amount": -7350, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior). At reconciled $49/SF (drawn from retrospective Pairs 1 & 2; Pair 3 outlier excluded with documented reasoning), the GLA adjustment is −$7,350. Cost support of $49.37/SF converges, providing IRS-defensible cross-validation."}}, "C2": {"bath": {"direction": "negative", "amount": -7100, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 2 has 3 full bathrooms versus the subject''s 2.5 (superior). The half-bath increment from two retrospective paired sales is approximately $7,100 (midpoint of $7,000–$7,200). Cost ($8,229) significantly exceeds paired sales, acting as a ceiling only."}}, "C3": {"date": {"direction": "positive", "amount": 8587, "method": "Market Conditions (Resale Pairs)", "rationale": "Comp 3 sold 9 months prior to the retrospective effective date (inferior date in an appreciating market). At reconciled 0.33%/mo: $289,000 × 9 × 0.33 ÷ 100 = $8,587. All resale pair data confirmed from pre-date-of-death period."}}}, "step4_adjusted_prices": {"C1": {"unadjusted": 318000, "adjusted": 310650}, "C2": {"unadjusted": 312500, "adjusted": 305400}, "C3": {"unadjusted": 289000, "adjusted": 297587}}, "step4_reconciliation_narrative": "Adjusted prices cluster in a tight band of approximately $297,587–$310,650 as of the retrospective effective date — a spread of approximately $13,000. The standard-level estate scenario introduces two important analytical challenges beyond the basic framework. First, the GLA paired sales divergence — Pair 3 at $58.00/SF vs. $48.33–$48.67 for Pairs 1 & 2 — must be identified, investigated, and excluded with written documentation; an unexplained inconsistency in IRS-reviewed appraisal creates audit risk. Second, the market conditions adjustment is introduced in the retrospective context — the resale pairs must be confirmed as pre-date-of-death transactions, and the derived appreciation rate must reflect the market as of the effective date rather than current conditions. The GLA cost indication ($49.37/SF) falls just above the consistent paired sales range, providing convergent support that strengthens defensibility under IRS review. The Fair Market Value opinion supporting the trust dissolution filing is well-centered in the $300,000–$308,000 range.", "tolerance_note": "Student answers are accepted within ±5% of model derived values for paired-sales calculations and within the indicated reconciliation range. Step 3 adjustments accepted within ±13% of the computed amount for GLA, ±12% for bath, and ±16% for market conditions."}'::jsonb
FROM scenarios s
JOIN scenario_categories sc ON sc.id = s.category_id
JOIN module_sections ms ON ms.id = sc.section_id
JOIN section_fields f ON f.section_id = ms.id AND f.field_key = 'adjustment_grid'
WHERE sc.code = 'M2-S4-C3'
  AND s.order_index = 2;

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- Scenario: 4512 Willowbrook Drive — Fractional Interest Valuation
-- Category M2-S4-C3 #3 · difficulty 'advanced'
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
INSERT INTO scenarios
  (category_id, order_index, difficulty, title, scenario_text)
SELECT id, 3,
  'advanced',
  '4512 Willowbrook Drive — Fractional Interest Valuation',
  'You are appraising a home at 4512 Willowbrook Drive, Anderson SC for an estate settlement involving a fractional interest, on referral from Carolinas Estate & Trust Group. The decedent owned a 60% undivided interest in this property at the time of death. Federal estate tax is assessed on the value of the interest actually held, not the full fee simple value. The retrospective effective date is the date of death, 20 months prior to today. The subject is a 2,400 SF home built in 2006 with three full bathrooms, a 2-car garage, in good condition, in a standard (non-amenitied) location.

The appraisal proceeds in two stages. The adjustment analysis (Steps 1–3) establishes the fee simple Fair Market Value of the whole property under IRS Revenue Ruling 59-60. Step 4 then presents both the fee simple conclusion and the discounted fractional interest value — a fractional interest discount is applied to reflect market resistance to co-ownership and the inability to independently control, sell, or encumber the property. Three closed sales are provided, differing across four adjustment types: GLA, location, condition, and market conditions. The GLA paired sales include an outlier (Pair 4) that must be excluded with documented reasoning. Comp 3 carries three simultaneous adjustments — GLA (positive), Location (negative, opposing direction), and Market Conditions (positive). Three of the four adjustment types lack cost support and rely entirely on market-derived paired sales. Identify the differing features, derive market-supported adjustments, apply them independently, and reconcile into your fee simple Fair Market Value as of the date of death; the fractional interest discount is then applied in Step 4.'
FROM scenario_categories WHERE code = 'M2-S4-C3';

