onciled adjustments to each comparable. Use NEGATIVE values for superior comps and POSITIVE for inferior. Comp 1 receives two negative adjustments (GLA + Location). Comp 2 receives one positive (Condition). Comp 3 receives three adjustments — GLA (positive, inferior), Location (negative, superior — opposing direction), and Market Conditions (positive). For Comp 3 (market conditions), calculate as: $374,000 × 11 months × your reconciled %/mo ÷ 100. All rationales must confirm data is from the retrospective period; address the GLA Pair 4 outlier exclusion in the GLA rationale; for Comp 3''s three adjustments, each must be independently justified.", "applicable": {"C1": ["gla", "loc"], "C2": ["cnd"], "C3": ["gla", "loc", "date"]}, "method_dropdown": ["Paired Sales Analysis", "Location Paired Sales Analysis", "Market Conditions (Resale Pairs)", "Cost-Based Support", "Grouped Paired Sales", "Regression Analysis", "Appraiser Judgment / Extraction"], "support_min_chars": 15}, "step4": {"show_net_gross_panel": true}}'::jsonb,
  '{"step1_correct_flags": {"C1": ["gla", "loc"], "C2": ["cnd"], "C3": ["gla", "loc", "date"]}, "step1_rationale": "Comp 1 differs in two superior features: 150 SF larger (GLA) and amenitied/gated location (Location) — both require negative adjustments. Comp 2 differs in only one feature: average condition versus the subject''s good condition (inferior, requires positive adjustment). Comp 3 differs in three features with opposing directions: 150 SF smaller (inferior GLA, positive adjustment), amenitied/gated location (superior Location, negative adjustment), and sold 11 months prior to the date of death (inferior Date, positive adjustment). Bathrooms, garage, and year built are equivalent. All adjustments reflect retrospective effective date conditions.", "step2_tables": {"paired": {"gla": {"pair_answers": [44.67, 46.67, 45.33, 60.0], "concluded_range": [44.0, 47.0], "rationale": "Pairs 1–3 cluster tightly at $44.67–$46.67/SF — strong, consistent retrospective market support. Pair 4 produces $60.00/SF and must be excluded with documented reasoning for IRS review (different submarket, anomalous transaction, or data anomaly). Bracket conclusion in the $44–$47/SF range."}, "loc": {"pair_answers": [15000, 15500, 16000, 17000], "concluded_range": [15000, 16000], "rationale": "Pairs 1–3 produce $15,000–$16,000 — tight retrospective market support. Pair 4 ($17,000) is a modest outlier; address but do not weight heavily. Reconcile within Pairs 1–3."}, "cnd": {"pair_answers": [12000, 12400, 12100], "concluded_range": [11900, 12500], "rationale": "Three retrospective pairs produce $12,000, $12,100, and $12,400 — a tight $400 spread, exceptionally consistent."}, "date": {"pair_answers": [0.328, 0.361, 0.351], "concluded_range": [0.32, 0.37], "rationale": "Three retrospective resale pairs produce 0.33%, 0.35%, and 0.36%/mo. Tight market support for monthly appreciation rate as of the date of death."}}, "cost": {"gla": {"answer": 50.64, "rationale": "$80.00 × (1 − 0.367) = $50.64/SF (retrospective). Falls above the consistent paired sales range of $44.67–$46.67/SF — a clear ceiling. Weight paired sales; cost confirms the upper bound is not exceeded."}}}, "step2_reconciliation": {"gla": {"range": [44.0, 47.0], "rationale": "Paired sales support $44.67–$46.67/SF (Pairs 1–3). Pair 4 ($60.00/SF) excluded with documented retrospective reasoning. Cost support of $50.64/SF is a clear ceiling. Reconcile near $46/SF, weighting paired sales."}, "loc": {"range": [15000, 16000], "rationale": "Paired sales support $15,000–$16,000 (Pairs 1–3). Pair 4 ($17,000) addressed but not weighted. No cost method applicable. Reconcile near the midpoint at approximately $15,250."}, "cnd": {"range": [11900, 12500], "rationale": "Three pairs produce $400 spread — exceptionally tight retrospective support. No cost method applicable. Reconcile near $12,000."}, "date": {"range": [0.33, 0.36], "rationale": "Paired sales support 0.33–0.36%/mo. No cost method applicable. Reconcile near 0.345%/mo."}}, "step3_adjustments": {"C1": {"gla": {"direction": "negative", "amount_per_unit": -46.0, "units": 150, "computed_amount": -6900, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior). At reconciled $46/SF (drawn from retrospective Pairs 1–3; Pair 4 outlier excluded with documented reasoning), the GLA adjustment is −$6,900. Cost support of $50.64/SF acts as a ceiling, confirming the conclusion is well-bounded."}, "loc": {"direction": "negative", "amount": -15250, "method": "Location Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 1 is in an amenitied/gated community (superior to the subject''s standard location). The location premium derived from three retrospective Pairs 1–3 is approximately $15,250 (midpoint of the $15,000–$16,000 range)."}}, "C2": {"cnd": {"direction": "positive", "amount": 12000, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 2 is in average condition versus the subject''s good condition (inferior). The condition increment from three tightly-clustered retrospective pairs ($12,000–$12,400) is approximately $12,000."}}, "C3": {"gla": {"direction": "positive", "amount_per_unit": 46.0, "units": 150, "computed_amount": 6900, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 3 is 150 SF smaller than the subject (inferior). At reconciled $46/SF, the GLA adjustment is +$6,900 — opposing direction from Comp 1''s GLA adjustment, demonstrating that GLA must be applied based on each comp''s relationship to the subject."}, "loc": {"direction": "negative", "amount": -15250, "method": "Location Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 3 is in an amenitied/gated community (superior). Same location premium as applied to Comp 1: approximately $15,250 negative. Comp 3 has opposing GLA (positive) and Location (negative) adjustments — both must be applied independently."}, "date": {"direction": "positive", "amount": 14193, "method": "Market Conditions (Resale Pairs)", "rationale": "Comp 3 sold 11 months prior to the date of death (inferior date in an appreciating market). At reconciled 0.345%/mo: $374,000 × 11 × 0.345 ÷ 100 = $14,193. All resale pair data confirmed from the pre-date-of-death period."}}}, "step4_adjusted_prices": {"C1": {"unadjusted": 398000, "adjusted": 375850}, "C2": {"unadjusted": 362000, "adjusted": 374000}, "C3": {"unadjusted": 374000, "adjusted": 379843}}, "step4_reconciliation_narrative": "Adjusted prices cluster in a tight band of approximately $374,000–$379,843 — a spread of less than $6,000 across three comparables and six total adjustments. The fee simple Fair Market Value as of the date of death is well-supported in the $375,000–$378,000 range. The fractional interest valuation then proceeds in stage two: the decedent''s 60% pro-rata share of approximately $376,000 is $225,600. A fractional interest discount of approximately 15% (within the 10–25% range typically supported in literature and market evidence for undivided residential interests) yields a fractional interest value of approximately $191,800. The discount reflects market resistance to co-ownership and the inability to independently control, sell, or encumber the property. The advanced-level teaching points are: (1) the GLA Pair 4 outlier ($60.00/SF) must be excluded with documented IRS-review reasoning, (2) three of four adjustment types lack cost support and rely entirely on retrospective paired sales evidence, (3) Comp 3''s opposing-direction GLA and Location adjustments demonstrate that net and gross adjustments tell different stories, and (4) the two-stage valuation process requires a separately-supported fractional interest discount conclusion in addition to the fee simple analysis. The full process supports the IRS Form 706 filing for the fractional interest.", "tolerance_note": "Student answers are accepted within ±5% of model derived values for paired-sales calculations and within the indicated reconciliation range. Step 3 adjustments accepted within ±13% of the computed amount for GLA, ±12% for location and condition, and ±16% for market conditions."}'::jsonb
FROM scenarios s
JOIN scenario_categories sc ON sc.id = s.category_id
JOIN module_sections ms ON ms.id = sc.section_id
JOIN section_fields f ON f.section_id = ms.id AND f.field_key = 'adjustment_grid'
WHERE sc.code = 'M2-S4-C3'
  AND s.order_index = 3;

-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- Scenario: 318 Clover Ridge Court — Pre-Purchase Advisory
-- Category M2-S4-C4 #1 · difficulty 'basic'
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
INSERT INTO scenarios
  (category_id, order_index, difficulty, title, scenario_text)
SELECT id, 1,
  'basic',
  '318 Clover Ridge Court — Pre-Purchase Advisory',
  'You are appraising a home at 318 Clover Ridge Court, Greer SC for a fee advisory engagement on behalf of Upstate Investment Partners. The client is an investor evaluating a potential acquisition of this property as a rental asset — there is no contract price, no lender, no court, and no regulatory audience. Your role is to provide an independent opinion of current market value to inform a business decision. The investor will use this opinion to determine whether and at what price to make an offer.

The subject is a 1,780 SF home built in 2003 with three bedrooms, two full bathrooms, and a 2-car garage, in good condition. Three closed sales are provided. Two require GLA adjustments (one larger, one smaller than the subject) and one requires a bathroom adjustment. The same analytical rigor applies as in regulated assignments — the investor client deserves the same quality of support — but the documentation style is advisory rather than regulatory: the rationale should explain what the market pays and why, not just cite technical methodology. Both cost indications in this scenario sit at or near the top of the paired sales range, providing convergent support without clearly acting as either floor or ceiling — the most common relationship between the two methods. Identify the differing features, derive market-supported adjustment values, apply them, and reconcile the adjusted prices into your advisory opinion of market value.'
FROM scenario_categories WHERE code = 'M2-S4-C4';

