Effective Age", "16 years"], ["Economic Life", "60 years"], ["Depreciation Rate", "26.7%"], ["Formula", "$14,000 × (1 − 0.267) = ?"]], "input_suffix": ""}]}], "reconciliation": {"instruction": "Review both method indications and enter your reconciled adjustment for each item. Both cost indications significantly exceed paired sales — clear ceilings in both cases. Weight paired sales. Market conditions reconciles directly from resale pairs.", "items": [{"feature_key": "gla", "label": "GLA Adjustment ($/SF)"}, {"feature_key": "bath", "label": "Bathroom Adjustment ($)"}, {"feature_key": "date", "label": "Market Conditions Adjustment (%/mo)"}]}}, "step3": {"instruction": "Apply your reconciled adjustments to each comparable. Use a NEGATIVE value where the comp is superior to the subject, and a POSITIVE value where it is inferior. Comps 1 and 2 each receive one negative adjustment. Comp 3 receives a positive market conditions adjustment — it sold 9 months ago in an appreciating market. Formula: $282,000 × 9 months × your reconciled %/mo ÷ 100. Each rationale should explain what the market pays and why — useful intelligence for the investor''s offer strategy.", "applicable": {"C1": ["gla"], "C2": ["bath"], "C3": ["date"]}, "method_dropdown": ["Paired Sales Analysis", "Market Conditions (Resale Pairs)", "Cost-Based Support", "Grouped Paired Sales", "Regression Analysis", "Appraiser Judgment / Extraction"], "support_min_chars": 15}, "step4": {"show_net_gross_panel": false}}'::jsonb,
  '{"step1_correct_flags": {"C1": ["gla"], "C2": ["bath"], "C3": ["date"]}, "step1_rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior GLA, single adjustment). Comp 2 has 3 full bathrooms versus the subject''s 2.5 (superior bath, single adjustment). Comp 3 sold 9 months ago in an appreciating market (inferior date, single adjustment). All other features are equivalent across all three comparables.", "step2_tables": {"paired": {"gla": {"pair_answers": [49.0, 48.0, 57.0], "concluded_range": [47.5, 58.0], "rationale": "Pairs 1 and 2 cluster tightly at $49.00 and $48.00/SF. Pair 3 diverges significantly to $57.00/SF and must be excluded with documented reasoning (different submarket, anomalous transaction, or data anomaly). For the advisory client, the explanation matters as much as the analysis: a sophisticated investor will ask why the outlier was excluded. Bracket conclusion toward Pairs 1 & 2."}, "bath": {"pair_answers": [7000, 7400], "concluded_range": [6900, 7500], "rationale": "Two pairs bracket the half-bath/full-bath increment at $7,000 and $7,400 — solid market support."}, "date": {"pair_answers": [0.323, 0.358, 0.286], "concluded_range": [0.28, 0.37], "rationale": "Three resale pairs produce 0.32%, 0.36%, and 0.29%/mo — wider spread than typical. Bracket toward central tendency near 0.32%/mo, with appreciation likely sitting in the 0.31–0.34%/mo range."}}, "cost": {"gla": {"answer": 57.91, "rationale": "$79.00 × (1 − 0.267) = $57.91/SF. Significantly above the consistent paired sales range ($48–$49/SF) — clear ceiling. The market does not pay full depreciated replacement cost for additional GLA at this vintage. Weight paired sales."}, "bath": {"answer": 10262, "rationale": "$14,000 × (1 − 0.267) = $10,262. Significantly exceeds paired sales of $7,000–$7,400. Clear ceiling — buyers pay less than cost to add a bathroom for this age. Weight paired sales."}}}, "step2_reconciliation": {"gla": {"range": [48.0, 50.0], "rationale": "Paired sales support $48–$49/SF (Pairs 1 & 2). Pair 3 ($57.00/SF) excluded with documented reasoning. Cost support of $57.91/SF is well above and acts only as a ceiling — the gap warrants advisory commentary that buyers consistently pay less than replacement cost for additional GLA. Reconcile near $49/SF."}, "bath": {"range": [7000, 7400], "rationale": "Paired sales bracket $7,000–$7,400. Cost ($10,262) significantly exceeds paired sales — large gap, clear ceiling. The investor should understand that buyers pay roughly two-thirds of replacement cost for bathroom additions at this vintage. Reconcile within the paired bracket."}, "date": {"range": [0.31, 0.34], "rationale": "Paired sales support a wider range of 0.29–0.36%/mo. No cost method applicable. Reconcile near central tendency at approximately 0.33%/mo."}}, "step3_adjustments": {"C1": {"gla": {"direction": "negative", "amount_per_unit": -49.0, "units": 150, "computed_amount": -7350, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 1 is 150 SF larger than the subject (superior). At reconciled $49/SF (Pairs 1 & 2; Pair 3 outlier excluded), the GLA adjustment is −$7,350. Cost support of $57.91/SF acts only as a ceiling — for the investor''s pricing intelligence, buyers in this market pay roughly $49/SF (~85% of depreciated replacement cost) for additional GLA at this vintage."}}, "C2": {"bath": {"direction": "negative", "amount": -7200, "method": "Paired Sales Analysis", "rationale": "Comp 2 has 3 full bathrooms versus the subject''s 2.5 (superior). The half-bath increment from two paired sales is approximately $7,200 (midpoint of $7,000–$7,400). Cost ($10,262) significantly exceeds paired sales — a clear ceiling. Buyers pay about 70% of replacement cost for bathroom additions in this market."}}, "C3": {"date": {"direction": "positive", "amount": 8375, "method": "Market Conditions (Resale Pairs)", "rationale": "Comp 3 sold 9 months ago in an appreciating market (inferior date). At reconciled 0.33%/mo: $282,000 × 9 × 0.33 ÷ 100 = $8,375. Three resale pairs support this rate, bringing Comp 3 in line with current market values."}}}, "step4_adjusted_prices": {"C1": {"unadjusted": 308000, "adjusted": 300650}, "C2": {"unadjusted": 303500, "adjusted": 296300}, "C3": {"unadjusted": 282000, "adjusted": 290375}}, "step4_reconciliation_narrative": "Adjusted prices range from approximately $290,375 to $300,650 — a spread of about $10,275 across three comparables and three different adjustment types. The advisory opinion of current market value is supported in the $293,000–$300,000 range, giving the investor a clear, well-supported benchmark for the acquisition decision. The standard-level scenario introduces three analytical layers beyond the basic framework. First, the GLA outlier exclusion (Pair 3 at $57.00/SF vs. $48–$49 for Pairs 1 & 2) must be documented and explained — a sophisticated investor will scrutinize the inputs. Second, the cost-vs-market gap is significant ($57.91/SF cost vs. $48–$49/SF market for GLA; $10,262 cost vs. $7,000–$7,400 market for bath), and the gap itself is actionable advisory information: it tells the investor the market is pricing improvements at well below replacement cost. Third, the market conditions adjustment brings Comp 3 in line with current market values. The investor''s opinion of value is independent of return objectives — market value reflects what a typical buyer would pay, not what would satisfy a specific cap rate or return hurdle.", "tolerance_note": "Student answers are accepted within ±5% of model derived values for paired-sales calculations and within the indicated reconciliation range. Step 3 adjustments accepted within ±13% of the computed amount for GLA, ±12% for bath, and ±16% for market conditions."}'::jsonb
FROM scenarios s
JOIN scenario_categories sc ON sc.id = s.category_id
